stry ultimately failed, in large part due to growing fears that film would corrupt the church by substituting an American “civil religion” in place of solid Christian values and amidst continuing Christian unease about the potential for the glorification of images to revert to idolatry. While radio eclipsed the motion picture as the Christian communication media of choice by the 1920, the early film makers had laid the foundations for the current re-emergence of Christian film and entertainment, from Veggie Tales to The Passion of the Christ.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristian filmsxHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aChristian filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures in Christian education. 0aMotion picturesxReligious aspectsxChristianityxUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSilent filmsxHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aSilent filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aChristian.  aCinema.  aSanctuary.  afilm.  afirst.  ahistory.  aindustry.  aorigins.  aprovides.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475210440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814753231.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814753231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814753231/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK